## Test isolation — nightly e2e browser suite no longer poisons routine runs

### Context

The routine command `uv run pytest -q -m "not scenario"` reported 58 failures
(MCP-integration schema tests + several async endpoint tests: `comment`,
`review`, `set-version-status`, `current-user`) with `RuntimeError: Runner.run()
cannot be called from a running event loop`. Root-caused to cross-suite
pollution, **not** feature code: `tests/units` alone (2693), `tests/mcp` alone
(25), and `mcp + units` together (2718) are all green; the 58 appear only once
`tests/e2e` is collected and run. The e2e suite drives a **session-scoped**
`sync_playwright` browser whose event loop stays alive in-process for the rest
of the session, breaking `pytest-asyncio` for every async test collected after
it. Marker-only deselection (`-m "not e2e"`) did not help because most e2e
tests were not tagged `e2e` — they still ran and started the browser. The e2e
suite is **nightly-only** by design (see `.cursor/08-testing-and-deployment`),
so it must not run in routine/agent runs.

### Changes

1. `tests/e2e/conftest.py`
   - Added `_e2e_explicitly_selected(config)` — true only when the caller
     clearly targets the suite (a `tests/e2e` path arg, `-m e2e`, or live mode
     via `ONTOBRICKS_LIVE_BASE`).
   - Extended `pytest_collection_modifyitems` to tag every non-scenario e2e
     test with the `e2e` marker and, unless the suite is explicitly targeted,
     add a `skip` marker. Skipped-at-collection tests never trigger the
     Playwright fixtures, so the session-scoped browser loop is never created
     during routine runs. Live-mode gating is preserved.

